			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-style: italic">A gust of wind can interrupt you in DAoC and you can't be in combat mode while casting.</span>
<br />

<br />
This isn't true. Only two things can interrupt spell-casting: moving and being attacked. Both of these will interrupt EQ spellcasting too.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">While the two systems are similar I would have to give higher marks to EQ's magic system overall.</span>
<br />

<br />
Hmm. I don't see how this can possibly be. Forgetting even the enormous downtime associated with being a caster in EQ (mind-numbing downtime), let's move right to the issue of viability. In EQ, several casting classes (most, as a matter of fact) are so gimped that no one plays them because they are useless at high levels. What I remember from my EQ days was that if you were unlucky enough to have chosen to play a Necro, Wizard, Mage, Druid or Ranger, you were screwed at higher levels because no one wanted you in their raids. Raids consisted of tanks, clerics, Enchanters and maybe a Mage or a Monk.
<br />

<br />
The whole spell system is so screwed up in EQ that it totally collapses at later levels. Wizards? Give me a break. The reason no one wanted wizzies in their groups in EQ was because at high levels, the mobs had INSANE magic resistance. They were essentially immune to magic attack. Nice balance, eh? The only reason people wanted Enchanters was for the mana battery, and this was practically a necessity since without them, downtime was grotesque.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Fizzling was frustrating in EQ but it was something you could work your way out of until it wasn't that frustrating anymore.</span>
<br />

<br />
And in DAOC, your spells don't fizzle, so there's nothing to work around in the first place.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic"> I have seen no way to work your way out of the way you can be interrupted in DAoC though.</span>
<br />

<br />
Really? Hmm. Maybe you could NOT ATTACK the mob with your staff? Maybe that would work. The only thing that will interrupt a spell in DAOC is if you move or you get attacked. If I remember, in EQ, getting attacked and moving interrupted your spell casting too. The only difference is that you cannot enter melee and cast spells at the same time. of course, once you get to level 20 or so in DAOC you avoid Melee like the plague because you know you're a caster and have no hit points, so this isn't even an issue.
<br />

<br />
Also, to return to the viability issue, in DAOC, your wizard spells actually work on high-level mobs, so you don't have to go after them with your stick. Revolutionary.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
